We are given with time instances when a bus will arrive in some other array like[1,3,4], where each bus has fixed capacity k(say 2).

Now, given this info, we have to print the index(1-based) of last kth person in Queue who boards bus at each time instance of bus arrival. If by the time bus arrives and no one boards bus, meaning queue empty, print 0.

Some of the questions asked were

- a tetrahedron with 3 corners a,b,c,d is given. find the number of ways to reach d from d in exactly n steps

- Q based on https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/bipartite-graph/

- make a data structure which has 2 functions insert(int key, string value) and cleanup().

    -- insert : if key is already present, concatenate value to the already present value corresponding to the key.

    -- cleanup : all the keys which haven't been updated or inserted in the past 5 minutes have to be removed.

    Expected time complexity for both operations: O(1)

You have k knights on a board. Two knights can swap their positions if they can capture each other. What is the total number of final configurations of the board?

3) You have a sorted doubly linked list. Convert it into a balanced BST in O(n) time and constant space.

For example arr = [6, 8, 10, 12, 8, 10]. We can firstly delete the subarray [8, 10, 12] to obtain arr = [6, 8, 10] then we can delete the whole array [6, 8, 10] to obtain an array of  length 0. So the answer will be 0.
    Solution Link:     minimum size of array by removing 3 consecutive elements with difference = k

IITR

(2 Ques) (9.2+ cg for chemical, [CSE, ECE, EE, Meta]>7.0, almost no other branches)

Q1-> N oranges. Minimum moves to reach 0 oranges. 1 move can be one of the three i.e. -> eat one orange(n-1), if n%2 == 0 then eat n//2 oranges, if n%3 == 0 then eat 2*(n//3) oranges. https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-days-to-eat-n-oranges

Sol -> BFS with saving seen states, AC.

Q2-> N distinct elements, calculate number of subsequences where A[i+1]%A[i] == 0. Elements can be reordered.

Sol -> Sort array in decreasing order. Then, use the LIS approach to count. 2 test cases TLE, => 88/100.
[use A DP Array dp[i]=(int)Math.pow(2,dp[i])  -> Got AC // After sorting get the nearest divisor of i (j in this case)]

Solution : This problem can be solved with the following recurrence: Let dp[i][j] be the number of ways to use the first i letters of s to end up at position j.

  • Base case: dp[0][x] = 1. All else is 0.
  • Recurrence: Set dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] (corresponds to don't use current character). Then, if s[i] (1-indexed) is l, add dp[i-1][j+1] (assuming j+1 <= n). Otherwise, add dp[i-1][j-1] (assuming j-1 >= 0).
  • Answer: The answer is dp[s.length][y]. Did this solution pass all test cases ? I think it is counting repeated subsequences too ?

Problem  (Codeforces) -  14D Two Paths      SPOJ TwoPaths : Solution Can you explain with the help of pseudocode? I took help from this. Rest is slight modification which includes answers from parent also.

                https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maximum-product-of-two-non-intersecting-paths-in-a-tree/ Same problem but the solution given

 is O(n^2). O(n) was needed.

Approach:

We are going to use dynamic programming, lets define some functions:

longestPath(vertex, parent) = length of the longest path in the tree rooted at vertex removing edge(vertex, parent)

longestLevel(vertex, parent) = maximum reachable level in the same tree.

Note: there are 2N-2 different states(vertex, parent), this allows us to compute all in O(N).

The answer is the maximum of longestPath(a, b) * longestPath(b, a) being (a, b) two endpoints of an edge (we must try everyone).

To compute longest path we need to handle these cases:

The longest path is the vertex itself.

The longest path is in one son of the sub tree rooted at vertex.

The longest path includes vertex and and goes through two distinct sons as deep as possible (there maybe be zero or one son, this is can be handled in the same code).

IITG (Difficulty: Easy)

  1. Find the count of all pairs of integers in an array such that their sum is a multiple of 60. One element can be present in multiple pairs. For example if the given  array is [20,40,100], answers are [20,40] and [20,100] => Use map. My AC solution: https://ide.geeksforgeeks.org/c00kzBzgbu
  2. Array Pruning :  Given an array,pick the maximum and second maximum element. If they are the same, delete both of them from the array, else delete the second maximum element and push (maximum-second_maximum) into the array. Find the last remaining element of the array. : Use Max Heap. Pop twice. If they are the same, continue, else push the absolute difference of the top 2 into the heap. Stop when size of heap becomes 1(return remaining element) or 0(return 0).
  3. Given a dictionary of strings of length upto 5*10^4. Find the longest sequence of words you can make from the dictionary, such that in any sequence, each consecutive word is one edit distance away from the previous word, and each word of the sequence is present in the dictionary. Edit distance of 1 means a string that can be formed by deleting exactly one character from the previous string. Example: Dictionary: {a,b,ba,bca,bda,bdca} Answer: 4 ( bdca->bda->ba->a, and there are other such sequences of length 4.)

=====> https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-string-chain/

 Solution: I used BFS from each word, by decreasing the length of this word by 1 unit in each level and checking if the new word exists in the dictionary or not.

Did anyone solve the second coding question (Minimum Price)? Please upload the soluton. An accepted solution was to compute the mini cost for each move and then take the overall minimum. so we iterate move from [0,n-1] and calculate the minimum cost. suppose we do  move  = m then for each element a[i] pick least from  a[i]....a[i+k] and sum for all i, this sum( min(a[i].....a[i+k]))+ x*m would be cost for m moves. you can do this in O(n^2) by storing the minimum values of all ai.

  1. Find all subarrays of size>=2 and whose gcd is maximum ( Just take subarrays of size 2 and check for all, that is answer)
  2. Longest non decreasing subarray (not subsequence)
  3. You are given a tree with n nodes, each node will have one character value from a to z.  Like you have a tree of 5 nodes, they can have values - [a,b,a,c,b]. The tree is rooted at 1. Now starting from the root node, each node with a character value joins itself to its nearest ancestor node with the same value. You have to calculate the size of each subtree of the tree. (DP on trees)
  4. You have 2*n numbers in array , n<=10. You can remove any two numbers in one round, and the score of that round is - gcd(number1,number2)*round_number , round number starts from 1. After round n all numbers are removed. Calculate maximum possible score that can be obtained after the game ends. ( Generating all permutations of the array was giving TLE, only 8/50 passed. I tried greedy, first find a pair with maximum gcd, multiply it with n and remove the numbers. Continue for n-1 rounds. It passed 45/50)
  5. Another was an ad-hoc question, you are given n numbers, you can  remove any of the numbers out of pair (a,b) and replace one with a+b, and other with -1. replace a if 2*a>=b and replace b if 2*b>=a. At end only one number remains, rest all are -1. Find the number of possible combinations for the final appearance of the number which doesnt get deleted.
